1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,801
What is the human way to handle this?

2
00:00:04,191 --> 00:00:08,000
People use different approaches to leadership situations.

3
00:00:08,111 --> 00:00:11,681
One approach is to assume the position of a dictator.

4
00:00:11,951 --> 00:00:16,321
The dictator makes all decisions without consulting those affected.

5
00:00:16,591 --> 00:00:22,161
He refuses to hear his subordinates side of a question because, deep down perhaps,

6
00:00:22,271 --> 00:00:27,201
he's afraid the subordinate might be right and this would cause him to lose face.

7
00:00:28,031 --> 00:00:30,321
Dictators don't last long.

8
00:00:30,510 --> 00:00:35,681
Employees may fake loyalty for a while, but unrest soon develops.

9
00:00:36,111 --> 00:00:42,161
Some of the best employees leave, and those remaining get together and plot against the tyrant.

10
00:00:42,431 --> 00:00:46,640
The result is that the organization ceases to function smoothly.

11
00:00:46,911 --> 00:00:50,880
This puts the dictator in a bad light with his superior.

12
00:00:52,111 --> 00:00:58,481
A second leadership technique is the cold, mechanical, I'm-a-rule-book-operator approach.

13
00:00:58,751 --> 00:01:03,601
The fellow using this approach handles everything exactly according to the book.

14
00:01:03,871 --> 00:01:10,801
He doesn't recognize that every rule or policy or plan is only a guide for the usual cases.

15
00:01:11,231 --> 00:01:17,360
This would-be leader treats human beings as machines, and of all things people don't like,

16
00:01:17,471 --> 00:01:21,201
perhaps the most disliked is being treated like a machine.

17
00:01:21,471 --> 00:01:25,681
The cold, impersonal efficiency expert is not an ideal.

18
00:01:25,951 --> 00:01:30,481
The machines that work for him develop only part of their energy.

19
00:01:31,151 --> 00:01:38,081
Persons who rise to tremendous leadership heights use a third approach that we call being human.

20
00:01:39,391 --> 00:01:49,120
Several years ago, I worked closely with John S., who is an executive in the engineering development section of a large aluminum manufacturer.

21
00:01:49,631 --> 00:01:54,481
John had mastered the Be Human approach and was enjoying its rewards.

22
00:01:54,751 --> 00:02:00,321
In dozens of little ways, John made his actions say, You are a human being.

23
00:02:00,511 --> 00:02:01,681
I respect you.

24
00:02:01,791 --> 00:02:04,640
I'm here to help you in every way I can.

25
00:02:05,711 --> 00:02:15,120
When an individual from another city joined his department, John went to considerable personal inconvenience to help him find suitable housing.

26
00:02:15,551 --> 00:02:23,441
Working through his secretary and two other women employees, he set up office birthday parties for each member of the staff.

27
00:02:23,711 --> 00:02:27,281
The thirty minutes or so required for this was not a cost.

28
00:02:27,391 --> 00:02:31,520
Rather, it was an investment in getting loyalty and output.

29
00:02:32,191 --> 00:02:36,880
When he learned that one of his staff members belonged to a minority faith,

30
00:02:36,991 --> 00:02:46,000
John called him in and explained that he would arrange for him to observe his religious holidays that don't coincide with the more common holidays.

31
00:02:47,151 --> 00:02:50,831
When an employee or someone in the employee's family was ill, John remembered.
